issue.title: Supporting multiprocessing models other than fork(2)
issue.body:
Greetings everyone,

As seen with #250 , anything Python changes might render "legacy" getmail unsupported. The changes from Python 2 to 3 made it obvious, but so are changes made within Python 3 (especially the change from `fork` to `spawn`,  unforeseen to me on MacOS with Python 3.8, and more recently on 3.14).

In the current state, getmail will have trouble with spawn, which is a shared concern between various actors. For Python multiprocessing (using `spawn`), pickle will be used for ser/des when spawning subprocesses, and pickle is limited in the type of objects it can handle (as seen in #250 ). Supporting this requires an extensive cleanup of `logging`, `tempfile` usage and `SSLContext` in getmail, as these objects are not pickable. One would even argue about serializing sensitive objects like SSLContext, but in the current use case the impact negligible.

After looking at it yesterday, I see different paths forward, but each have their tradeoffs @rpuntaie :
- use force fork method, as [suggested in Python docs](https://docs.python.org/3/library/multiprocessing.html#contexts-and-start-methods). The tradeoff is that if getmail ends up multithreading "unknowingly" [like it might happen on MacOS with higher level libs](https://github.com/python/cpython/issues/77906), getmail will crash. (Note: the issue would be the exact same with the legacy method of os.fork(2) of getmail5);
- patch getmail classes to support spawn. From my short testing, it involves dropping the custom-made logging class and use Python logging module instead (which seems to be onpar feature-wise, [original comment](https://github.com/getmail6/getmail6/blob/83ca7adfaaef9482a887be5126d18f2c6feeb74e/getmailcore/logging.py#L7) does not seem to apply any more), redesign the temporary files communication between parent <> child, and prevent [SSLContext sharing between processes](https://github.com/getmail6/getmail6/blob/83ca7adfaaef9482a887be5126d18f2c6feeb74e/getmailcore/_retrieverbases.py#L126). Tradeoff: significant departure from legacy, and extensive testing ahead.

To address this, you should ensure that only one movement coroutine runs per text object at any given time. A good approach is to stop any existing movement coroutine for a text object before starting a new one. You can achieve this by maintaining a reference to the running coroutine (e.g., in a Dictionary) and stopping it before you start a new one.

Adds certificate management script

Introduces a Bash script to automate certificate creation and management for Deadline 10 deployments.

This script simplifies the process of generating a CA, issuing server and client certificates, exporting PFX bundles, and importing the server certificate into AWS ACM. It also stores the ACM certificate ARN into SSM Parameter Store.

Prevents unintentional tracking of local Deadline 10 scripts,
which are not part of the project's core source code.

Adds private load balancer stack

Introduces a new CloudFormation stack for creating a private Application Load Balancer (ALB) for Deadline.

The private ALB facilitates internal communication and access to Deadline services within the VPC.
It also simplifies management of deadline certificates via SSM.

fix: Escape dots in release workflow tag patterns

in regex. Changed to escaped dots (\.) to match literal dots only.
This ensures the workflow only triggers on semantic version tags
like 0.0.1 and not on other patterns.
